Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.00,0:00:01.47,ENG,,0,0,0,,Hey! You hear that?
Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.00,0:00:01.47,CHN,,0,0,0,,嘿  你能听到吗
Dialogue: 0,0:00:01.47,0:00:02.82,CHN,,0,0,0,,*滋滋声*
Dialogue: 0,0:00:02.82,0:00:05.26,ENG,,0,0,0,,All kinds of electronics make this sound.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:02.82,0:00:05.26,CHN,,0,0,0,,所有电器都有这种滋滋声
Dialogue: 0,0:00:05.26,0:00:07.01,ENG,,0,0,0,,But why? Well, in some cases,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:05.26,0:00:07.01,CHN,,0,0,0,,这是为什么呢？有时候
Dialogue: 0,0:00:07.01,0:00:09.90,ENG,,0,0,0,,the sound comes from interactions between the wire and the air.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:07.01,0:00:09.90,CHN,,0,0,0,,声音是由导线与空气间的相互作用产生的
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.90,0:00:14.34,ENG,,0,0,0,,But in most cases, the answer has to do with how we deliver electricity.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.90,0:00:14.34,CHN,,0,0,0,,但大多数情况下  其原因跟我们传输电能的方法有关
Dialogue: 0,0:00:14.34,0:00:17.02,ENG,,0,0,0,,To power things, we send out particles called electrons.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:14.34,0:00:17.02,CHN,,0,0,0,,要让电器动起来  我们需要向它发送“电子”这种粒子
Dialogue: 0,0:00:17.02,0:00:19.10,ENG,,0,0,0,,And we call those moving electrons current.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:17.02,0:00:19.10,CHN,,0,0,0,,我们把移动的电子称为“电流”
Dialogue: 0,0:00:19.10,0:00:20.48,ENG,,0,0,0,,There are different types of current,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:19.10,0:00:20.48,CHN,,0,0,0,,电流可分为不同的种类
Dialogue: 0,0:00:20.48,0:00:23.87,ENG,,0,0,0,,but many things run on alternating current or A/C.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:20.48,0:00:23.87,CHN,,0,0,0,,而大部分电器接受的是交流电  也写作 A/C
Dialogue: 0,0:00:23.87,0:00:27.90,ENG,,0,0,0,,Here, as the electrons move along, they periodically reverse direction.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:23.87,0:00:27.90,CHN,,0,0,0,,交流电里的电子移动时会周期性地改变方向
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.90,0:00:31.60,ENG,,0,0,0,,Now, here’s the thing: Currents create magnetic fields.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.90,0:00:31.60,CHN,,0,0,0,,关键点来了：电流会产生磁场
Dialogue: 0,0:00:31.60,0:00:34.70,ENG,,0,0,0,,And with alternating current, those fields are constantly changing
Dialogue: 0,0:00:31.60,0:00:34.70,CHN,,0,0,0,,而交流电所产生的磁场会不断变化
Dialogue: 0,0:00:34.70,0:00:36.58,ENG,,0,0,0,,as the electrons move back and forth.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:34.70,0:00:36.58,CHN,,0,0,0,,会随着电子往复而变化
Dialogue: 0,0:00:36.58,0:00:40.03,ENG,,0,0,0,,Turns out, that change is enough to push and pull on nearby metal
Dialogue: 0,0:00:36.58,0:00:40.03,CHN,,0,0,0,,变化的磁场足以拉扯周边的金属
Dialogue: 0,0:00:40.03,0:00:41.19,ENG,,0,0,0,,and make it vibrate.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:40.03,0:00:41.19,CHN,,0,0,0,,也就是使其振动
Dialogue: 0,0:00:41.19,0:00:44.23,ENG,,0,0,0,,And like a plucked guitar string, that produces sound.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:41.19,0:00:44.23,CHN,,0,0,0,,这就像被手拨动的吉他弦  会产生声音
Dialogue: 0,0:00:44.23,0:00:47.82,ENG,,0,0,0,,Specifically, in the US, that always gets you a slightly out-of-tune B-flat.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:44.23,0:00:47.82,CHN,,0,0,0,,更确切地说  在美国  电线噪音的调子总是略有走音的B{\fnNoto Sans CJK SC\b1}♭
Dialogue: 0,0:00:47.82,0:00:51.80,ENG,,0,0,0,,That’s because the alternating current here switches 60 times per second,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:47.82,0:00:51.80,CHN,,0,0,0,,这是因为美国交流电的频率是60赫兹
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.33,0:00:55.40,Caption,,0,0,0,,{\fs76\an5\pos(1020,785)\fad(0,333)}欧洲大部、亚太\N和非洲的市电频率\N是 50Hz
Dialogue: 0,0:00:51.80,0:00:55.53,ENG,,0,0,0,,so the metal always vibrates at that frequency — or at a multiple of it.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:51.80,0:00:55.53,CHN,,0,0,0,,所以金属的振动频率要么等于这个值  要么就是这个值的倍数
Dialogue: 0,0:00:55.53,0:00:57.65,ENG,,0,0,0,,And that gets you this note.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:55.53,0:00:57.65,CHN,,0,0,0,,这就会产生这个调子{\fsp-30}：
Dialogue: 0,0:00:57.65,0:00:59.99,CHN,,0,0,0,,*略有走音的B♭*
